00:00:56,799 --> 00:00:59,519
might want to take if you want to

34
00:00:57,840 --> 00:01:01,520
improve your presentation skills. But

35
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:03,680
first, let's get into the tips. Starting

36
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:05,439
with the absolute most important element

37
00:01:03,679 --> 00:01:08,079
of any presentation that you're ever

38
00:01:05,438 --> 00:01:09,838
going to give, which is the idea. The

39
00:01:08,079 --> 00:01:11,039
underlying idea or concept that you're

40
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:12,560
trying to communicate with your audience

41
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:14,399
is the beating heart of your

42
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:16,399
presentation. As Chris Anderson, the

43
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:17,839
creator of TED puts it, "Your number one

44
00:01:16,400 --> 00:01:19,679
mission as a speaker is to take

45
00:01:17,840 --> 00:01:21,599
something that matters deeply to you and

46
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:22,720
to rebuild it inside the minds of your

47
00:01:21,599 --> 00:01:24,797
listeners." And that's what

48
00:01:22,719 --> 00:01:26,477
communication is all about. taking your

49
00:01:24,799 --> 00:01:27,839
ideas and sharing them with people who

50
00:01:26,478 --> 00:01:29,438
are willing to listen. And when it comes

51
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:31,199
to presentations, it's especially

52
00:01:29,438 --> 00:01:32,797
important to highlight this because a

53
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:33,999
lot of people are concerned with how

54
00:01:32,799 --> 00:01:35,520
they're going to look or how they're

55
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,119
going to sound on stage. And they don't

56
00:01:35,519 --> 00:01:38,878
give as much thought to the substance

57
00:01:37,118 --> 00:01:40,477
and the meaning of the idea that they're

58
00:01:38,879 --> 00:01:42,478
communicating. But in truth, the

59
00:01:40,478 --> 00:01:43,998
substance of that idea matters so much

60
00:01:42,478 --> 00:01:45,757
more than how you look while you're

61
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,839
delivering it. So before you ever step

62
00:01:45,759 --> 00:01:49,759
on a stage, understand all the details

63
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:51,679
of your idea. Understand why your

64
00:01:49,759 --> 00:01:53,199
audience should learn about this idea.

65
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:55,360
and make sure that each part of your

66
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:57,280
presentation relates to that idea and

67
00:01:55,359 --> 00:01:58,959
supports it. So once you've nailed down

68
00:01:57,280 --> 00:02:00,320
the idea behind your presentation, it's

69
00:01:58,959 --> 00:02:01,599
time to start looking at some tactics

70
00:02:00,319 --> 00:02:03,519
that you can use to make that

71
00:02:01,599 --> 00:02:04,958
presentation more compelling. And the

72
00:02:03,519 --> 00:02:06,559
first one I want to talk about is

73
00:02:04,959 --> 00:02:08,237
storytelling. The human brain is

74
00:02:06,560 --> 00:02:10,080
fundamentally wired to be drawn in by a

75
00:02:08,239 --> 00:02:11,520
good story. And storytelling is probably

76
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:13,599
the mode of communication that we are

77
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:15,439
most receptive to. Also, telling a story

78
00:02:13,598 --> 00:02:16,957
is a great way to add emotion to your

79
00:02:15,439 --> 00:02:18,958
talk. And that's especially useful when

80
00:02:16,959 --> 00:02:20,479
your idea isn't all that emotional

81
00:02:18,959 --> 00:02:21,760
fundamentally. For instance, back when

82
00:02:20,479 --> 00:02:23,278
the movie Prometheus was about to come

83
00:02:21,759 --> 00:02:26,159
out, the marketing team put out this

84
00:02:23,280 --> 00:02:27,839
fake 2023 TED talk where the CEO of Whan

85
00:02:26,159 --> 00:02:29,918
Industries, Peter Whan, comes out and he

86
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:31,759
gives this talk about human progression.

87
00:02:29,919 --> 00:02:33,439
And it's a pretty self argrandizing talk

88
00:02:31,759 --> 00:02:35,038
that's basically meant to build up him

89
00:02:33,439 --> 00:02:36,878
and his company in the eyes of the

90
00:02:35,039 --> 00:02:38,958
audience. But he starts out this talk

91
00:02:36,878 --> 00:02:40,639
with a story about the Titan Prometheus

92
00:02:38,959 --> 00:02:42,640
stealing fire from the gods and giving

93
00:02:40,639 --> 00:02:44,478
it to humanity as their first piece of

94
00:02:42,639 --> 00:02:46,078
true technology. and he gets into these

95
00:02:44,479 --> 00:02:47,598
ugly and kind of disgusting details

96
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:49,919
about the punishment that the gods used

97
00:02:47,598 --> 00:02:51,998
on Prometheus after he did this. And

98
00:02:49,919 --> 00:02:54,159
while this isn't all that related to the

99
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,719
progress of technology, it's a great way

100
00:02:54,159 --> 00:02:58,559
to add some visceral emotion and imagery

101
00:02:56,719 --> 00:02:59,919
to the talk that's otherwise kind of

102
00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:01,280
sterile. Now, if you're going to add a

103
00:02:59,919 --> 00:03:02,878
story to your talk, you need to know the

104
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:04,480
elements of great storytelling. And

105
00:03:02,878 --> 00:03:06,317
there are three main elements I want to

106
00:03:04,479 --> 00:03:07,918
talk about here. Number one, any good

107
00:03:06,318 --> 00:03:09,919
story needs to have a character that the

108
00:03:07,919 --> 00:03:11,758
audience can empathize with. And here I

109
00:03:09,919 --> 00:03:13,758
want to note that personal stories can

110
00:03:11,759 --> 00:03:15,598
be especially effective at forging a

111
00:03:13,759 --> 00:03:17,839
connection between you and your

112
00:03:15,598 --> 00:03:19,439
audience, especially if that story shows

113
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:21,199
a little bit of vulnerability on your

114
00:03:19,439 --> 00:03:22,479
part. You also need a conflict or some

115
00:03:21,199 --> 00:03:24,158
sort of problem. Basically, the thing

116
00:03:22,479 --> 00:03:25,999
that makes your audience curious and

117
00:03:24,158 --> 00:03:27,839
interested in the story. And finally,

118
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,318
you need a satisfying conclusion that

119
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:31,679
ties back into your idea. And on a

120
00:03:30,318 --> 00:03:33,278
related note, you've probably heard that

121
00:03:31,680 --> 00:03:35,360
telling a story can be a great way to

122
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:37,839
open a presentation or speech. And this

123
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:39,360
is true, but there's a catch. As the

124
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:41,040
author Michael Port puts it in his book,

125
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:43,199
Steal the Show, if you're opening with a

126
00:03:41,039 --> 00:03:44,478
story, it had better be a great story.

127
00:03:43,199 --> 00:03:45,998
Otherwise, open with a note that's

128
00:03:44,479 --> 00:03:47,838
intellectually or philosophically

129
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,359
important. Often, when a speaker starts

130
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:51,279
with a story, many in the audience

131
00:03:49,360 --> 00:03:53,199
think, "Oh boy, here comes another one

132
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:54,639
of those dull opening stories." In other

133
00:03:53,199 --> 00:03:55,919
words, we're all pretty jaded when it

134
00:03:54,639 --> 00:03:57,759
comes to the typical way that people

135
00:03:55,919 --> 00:03:59,278
structure their talks. After all, most

136
00:03:57,759 --> 00:04:01,678
of us have sat in school from anywhere

137
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:03,680
between 18 to 30 years. So, we've sat

138
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:05,119
through a lot of presentations and we've

139
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:06,799
seen it all. So, if you're using an

140
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:08,479
opening story as a crutch, people are

141
00:04:06,799 --> 00:04:10,080
going to catch on right away and it's

142
00:04:08,479 --> 00:04:11,679
going to hurt you. Now, in addition to

143
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:13,200
storytelling, another tactic you can use

144
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:15,200
to connect with your audience is to use

145
00:04:13,199 --> 00:04:17,118
analogies and metaphors to essentially

146
00:04:15,199 --> 00:04:18,957
meet your audience where they are. Using

147
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:20,479
an analogy is a great way to explain

148
00:04:18,959 --> 00:04:22,320
something in terms that your audience is

149
00:04:20,478 --> 00:04:23,599
going to easily understand. And a really

150
00:04:22,319 --> 00:04:25,439
good example of this comes from the

151
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:27,280
movie The Big Short, which is one of my

152
00:04:25,439 --> 00:04:28,718
favorite recent films. Now, in case

153
00:04:27,279 --> 00:04:30,319
you're unfamiliar with this movie, it's

154
00:04:28,720 --> 00:04:32,639
basically a story of how the great

155
00:04:30,319 --> 00:04:34,158
financial crash of 2008 happened. And in

156
00:04:32,639 --> 00:04:35,599
telling that story, the movie tries to

157
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:37,360
explain the inner workings of some of

158
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:39,280
the outright fraudulent financial

159
00:04:37,360 --> 00:04:40,560
inventions that helped to cause it. One

160
00:04:39,279 --> 00:04:43,198
of those inventions is called a

161
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:44,560
collateralized debt obligation or a CDO.

162
00:04:43,199 --> 00:04:46,719
But instead of just trying to straight

163
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:48,479
up explain this purposely complicated

164
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:49,999
financial instrument, they create an

165
00:04:48,478 --> 00:04:51,679
analogy that's much easier to

166
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,120
understand. After Ryan Gosling's

167
00:04:51,680 --> 00:04:54,880
character introduces the concept, the

168
00:04:53,120 --> 00:04:56,559
camera pans over to Anthony Bourdain,

169
00:04:54,879 --> 00:04:57,999
the famous chef. And then he creates a

170
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:59,839
story about how he bought fish on

171
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:01,279
Friday, but then three days later, it's

172
00:04:59,839 --> 00:05:03,278
getting kind of rotten. but instead of

173
00:05:01,279 --> 00:05:05,038
throwing away, he just throws it into a

174
00:05:03,279 --> 00:05:07,037
stew and calls it something new. And

175
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:09,440
that creates a much easier to understand

176
00:05:07,038 --> 00:05:11,278
picture of how CDIO works. And it's much

177
00:05:09,439 --> 00:05:13,119
more emotionally visceral as well, since

178
00:05:11,279 --> 00:05:15,037
most people have smelled rotten fish,

179
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:16,879
but don't even know what a CDIO is.

180
00:05:15,038 --> 00:05:18,239
Also, analogies and metaphors give you

181
00:05:16,879 --> 00:05:19,758
access to yet another tool for

182
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:21,759
connecting with your audience, and that

183
00:05:19,759 --> 00:05:23,198
is humor. And one of the masters at

184
00:05:21,759 --> 00:05:25,038
using this type of humor that I think

185
00:05:23,199 --> 00:05:26,638
you should study is John Oliver. Even

186
00:05:25,038 --> 00:05:28,319
though his show covers topics that are

187
00:05:26,639 --> 00:05:30,720
objectively boring, like the federal

188
00:05:28,319 --> 00:05:32,319
budget and gerrymandering and the IRS,

189
00:05:30,720 --> 00:05:33,999
millions of people still tune in to

190
00:05:32,319 --> 00:05:35,918
watch it because Jon is an expert at

191
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,758
using analogies to tie those boring

192
00:05:35,918 --> 00:05:39,197
topics to things that are funnier. For

193
00:05:37,759 --> 00:05:41,279
example, in one episode, he takes the

194
00:05:39,199 --> 00:05:43,280
IRS's practice of literally hanging up

195
00:05:41,279 --> 00:05:45,279
on its own customers, which they call a

196
00:05:43,279 --> 00:05:47,118
courtesy disconnect, and ties it to

197
00:05:45,279 --> 00:05:48,879
other things whose names hide their true

198
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:50,479
meaning, like the Care Bears, who are

199
00:05:48,879 --> 00:05:52,318
still vicious bears. And if you can

200
00:05:50,478 --> 00:05:54,079
learn to do this as well, especially in

201
00:05:52,319 --> 00:05:55,439
a way that connects with your specific

202
00:05:54,079 --> 00:05:57,679
audience, you're going to gain their

203
00:05:55,439 --> 00:05:59,038
trust and keep them much more engaged

204
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:00,720
throughout the entirety of your

205
00:05:59,038 --> 00:06:02,078
presentation. The last tactic I want to

206
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:03,440
talk about today is audience

207
00:06:02,079 --> 00:06:04,958
interaction. Because if you can take

208
00:06:03,439 --> 00:06:06,718
your audience and get them actively

209
00:06:04,959 --> 00:06:08,718
involved in the presentation, then you

210
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:10,880
can improve that presentation by a huge

211
00:06:08,720 --> 00:06:12,400
margin. And to explain how to do this, I

212
00:06:10,879 --> 00:06:14,318
want to tell you a story from my own

213
00:06:12,399 --> 00:06:15,838
life. So back in 2012, when I was still

214
00:06:14,319 --> 00:06:17,839
a college senior, I flew to New York

215
00:06:15,839 --> 00:06:19,439
City for a conference called Blog World.

216
00:06:17,839 --> 00:06:20,959
I was a blogger at the time. was pretty

217
00:06:19,439 --> 00:06:22,238
small and I had a lot of heroes that

218
00:06:20,959 --> 00:06:23,999
were going to be there who we really

219
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:25,360
wanted to see. So on the second day of

220
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,638
the conference, my friend Alex and I

221
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:28,638
went to go see one of our favorite

222
00:06:26,639 --> 00:06:29,840
bloggers give a talk, but we couldn't

223
00:06:28,639 --> 00:06:31,519
get into the room because it was

224
00:06:29,839 --> 00:06:32,637
standing room only and there was so many

225
00:06:31,519 --> 00:06:34,317
people packed in that there were

226
00:06:32,639 --> 00:06:36,240
literally people in the hallway trying

227
00:06:34,319 --> 00:06:37,680
to hear what he had to say. So instead

228
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:39,759
of getting into the mosh pit ourselves,

229
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:41,758
my friend Alex says, "Hey, let's go see

230
00:06:39,759 --> 00:06:43,600
this guy Marcus Sheridan speak instead."

231
00:06:41,759 --> 00:06:45,360
And we go into his room. It's much less

232
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:47,519
packed and it turns out that Marcus is a

233
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:48,880
pool salesman. So, I'm thinking this guy

234
00:06:47,519 --> 00:06:50,958
probably doesn't have a whole lot for

235
00:06:48,879 --> 00:06:53,279
me. But by the end of his speech, I was

236
00:06:50,959 --> 00:06:55,197
convinced that Marcus was hands down the

237
00:06:53,279 --> 00:06:57,037
best presenter at the entire conference.

238
00:06:55,199 --> 00:06:59,280
And the reason for this was that Marcus

239
00:06:57,038 --> 00:07:01,278
was an expert at audience interaction.

240
00:06:59,279 --> 00:07:03,758
And more importantly, he made his

241
00:07:01,279 --> 00:07:05,198
audience feel special. My most intense

242
00:07:03,759 --> 00:07:06,560
memory from the presentation is when he

243
00:07:05,199 --> 00:07:09,199
put up a slide on the projector that

244
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:12,319
just said October 10th, 2008. And

245
00:07:09,199 --> 00:07:13,918
underneath there was the number 7,882.

246
00:07:12,319 --> 00:07:16,239
And then he asked the audience, "Does

247
00:07:13,918 --> 00:07:17,918
anybody know what this number means and

248
00:07:16,240 --> 00:07:19,440
why it relates to this date?" And

249
00:07:17,918 --> 00:07:21,519
because I had been taking an economics

250
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:23,119
class, I raised my hand and I said, "I

251
00:07:21,519 --> 00:07:25,597
think that's the number the Dow Jones

252
00:07:23,120 --> 00:07:27,520
fell to on October 2008 during the stock

253
00:07:25,598 --> 00:07:29,118
market crash," which was the right

254
00:07:27,519 --> 00:07:31,278
answer. And Marcus came over and said,

255
00:07:29,120 --> 00:07:33,759
"My man, this guy knows what's up." And

256
00:07:31,279 --> 00:07:35,758
he made me feel so special that I had

257
00:07:33,759 --> 00:07:37,679
like absolute wrapped attention for the

258
00:07:35,759 --> 00:07:39,759
rest of the entire presentation. And I

259
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:41,199
loved it. Now, Marcus is a great speaker

260
00:07:39,759 --> 00:07:43,120
across the board. He's got a lot of

261
00:07:41,199 --> 00:07:44,638
energy. He's really engaging and he has

262
00:07:43,120 --> 00:07:47,039
a lot of practice doing this type of

263
00:07:44,639 --> 00:07:48,720
audience interaction. But still, if you

264
00:07:47,038 --> 00:07:50,638
can learn to do this, you're going to

265
00:07:48,720 --> 00:07:52,159
have a lot more success in your own

266
00:07:50,639 --> 00:07:54,159
presentations. But I do want to give you

267
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:55,680
a couple of warnings. Number one, don't

268
00:07:54,160 --> 00:07:57,360
start your presentation off with

